{"title_page": "Marvin O'Connor (basketball)", "text_new": "{{Under construction}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name            = Marvin O'Connor\n| image           = \n| width           =\n| caption         = \n| team            = \n| league          =\n| position        = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 4\n| weight_lb       = 200\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1978|07|11}}\n| birth_place     = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| nationality     = American\n| high_school     = [[Simon Gratz High School|Simon Gratz]]<br>(Philadelphia, Pennsylvania)\n| college         = [[Villanova Wildcats men's basketball|Villanova]] (1997\u20131998)<br>[[Saint Joseph's Hawks men's basketball|Saint Joseph's]] (1999\u20132002)\n| draft_year      = 2002\n| draft_round     = \n| draft_pick      = \n| draft_team      = \n| career_start    = 2002\n| career_end      = 2003\n| years1          = 2002\u20132003\n| team1           = [[KK Partizan|Partizan]]\n| highlights   =\n*[[Robert V. Geasey Trophy]] (2001)\n*Second-team All-[[Atlantic 10 Conference|Atlantic 10]] (2002)\n*First-team All-Atlantic 10 (2001)\n*Third-team All-Atlantic 10 (2000)\n| bbr             =\n}}\n'''Marvin O'Connor''' (born July 11, 1978) is an American former professional basketball player. He played [[high school basketball]] at [[Simon Gratz High School|Simon Gratz]] in his native [[Philadelphia]], winning the [[Philadelphia Public League]] title as a senior in 1997. After his freshman year in college at [[Villanova Wildcats men's basketball|Villanova]], O'Connor transferred to [[St. Joseph's Hawks men's basketball|St. Joseph's]], where he was an all-conference selection in all of his three seasons there, and won the [[Robert V. Geasey Trophy]] as the best basketball player in the [[Philadelphia Big 5]] in 2001. He went undrafted in the [[2002 NBA draft]] and spent his only professional season with [[KK Partizan]] in [[Serbia]], playing in the [[2002\u201303 Euroleague]]. He is a member of the St. Joseph's Hawks Hall of Fame (inducted in 2008) and of the Big 5 Hall of Fame (2013).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://saintjoseph_ftp.sidearmsports.com/custompages/attachments1/files/31200/639393.pdf|title=Saint Joseph's Men's Basketball 2018-19 Media Guide|year=2018|page=143\u201314|publisher=St. Joseph's University|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== High school career ==\nO'Connor was born in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] in 1978, to Alfred and Alexandria Dockins.<ref name=signature>{{Cite news|title=Villanova gets fast signature from Gratz guard O'Connor|author=Smith, Marcia C.|date=November 21, 1996|newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|page=57}}</ref> He attended [[Simon Gratz High School]], where he was named a starter as a sophomore in 1994\u201395 by coach Bill Ellerbee.<ref name=winning>{{Cite web|url=https://tedsilary.com/billellerbee107.htm|title=A Look at Simon Gratz High's 107-Game Winning Streak In Public League Regular Season Games, 1989-1998|website=tedsilary.com|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> That season, he scored a season-high 20 points against [[Central High School (Philadelphia)|Central]].<ref name=winning /> In the following season, his junior year, O'Connor was one of the main players on the team,<ref name=signature /> and was the team's top scorer in 11 out of 14 regular season games in the [[Philadelphia Public League]].<ref name=winning /> He scored a regular season-best 24 points against [[Roxborough High School|Roxborough]],<ref name=winning /> 29 points in the semfinals against [[Frankford High School|Frankford]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tedsilary.com/archive/BBPLplayoffs91-.htm|title=Philadelphia High School Basketball Public League Playoff Recaps, 1991-2004|website=tedsilary.com|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> and 35 points (a then-career high) against [[Edison/Fareira High School|Thomas Edison High School]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tedsilary.com/edison96.htm|title=A Look at Thomas Edison's 1995-96 Public League Champions|website=tedsilary.com|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> At the end of the season he was named in the All-City Second Team and in the All-Public League First Team after averaging 15.6 points per game.<ref name=ellerbee>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tedsilary.com/billellerbee.htm|title=A Look at Bill Ellerbee's 20-Year Coaching Career at Simon Gratz High (1983-2002)|website=tedsilary.com|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tedsilary.com/archive/BB1996recap.htm|title=Philadelphia Scholastic Basketball, 1996|website=tedsilary.com|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn O'Connor's senior season, he led the team in scoring in 10 out of 16 games during the Public League, including 39 points against [[Olney High School|Olney]] (a new career-high), 34 against [[Samuel S. Fels High School|Fels]] and 30 against [[Northeast High School (Philadelphia)|Northeast]].<ref name=winning /> During the playoffs, O'Connor scored 22 points in the semifinals against [[Strawberry Mansion High School|Strawberry Mansion]], and 14 points, along with 13 rebounds, in the championship game win against Engineering and Science, which was led by [[Lynn Greer]].<ref name=97recap>{{Cite web|url=https://tedsilary.com/archive/BB1997recap.htm|title=Philadelphia Scholastic Basketball, 1997|website=tedsilary.com|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> At the end of the year, O'Connor was named in the All-Public League and All-City First Teams,<ref name=ellerbee /> after averaging 23.7 points per game.<ref name=97recap /> The ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer|Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' named him City Player of the Year.<ref name=villanova>{{Cite web|url=https://villanova.com/news/1999/6/21/Q_amp_A_with_Marvin_O_Connor.aspx|title=Q & A with Marvin O'Connor|date=February 11, 1998|website=villanova.com|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> O'Connor scored a total 1,258 points at Simon Gratz.<ref name=ellerbee />\n\n== College career ==\nO'Connor was highly recruited in high school and received offers from several [[NCAA Division I]] programs, drawing interest from [[Clemson Tigers men's basketball|Clemson]], [[Xavier Musketeers men's basketball|Xavier]], [[NC State Wolfpack men's basketball|NC State]], [[Miami Hurricanes men's basketball|Miami (FL)]], [[Penn Quakers men's basketball|Penn]],<ref name=villanova /> [[Penn State Nittany Lions men's basketball|Penn State]], [[Temple Owls men's basketball|Temple]], [[UMass Minutemen basketball|UMass]], and [[Villanova Wildcats men's basketball|Villanova]].<ref name=signature /> He signed to play for Villanova in late November 1996.<ref name=signature /> As a true freshman at Villanova, O'Connor found little playing time under coach [[Steve Lappas]], starting 5 out of 21 games, and scoring a season-high 12 points against Temple.<ref name=nba>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.nba.com/draft2002/profiles/marvin_oconnor.html|title=Marvin O'Connor|website=[[NBA.com]]|year=2002|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> At the end of the season he had averages of 4.7 points, 1.7 rebounds and 1.2 assists per game.\n\nAfter the end of his first season at Villanova, O'Connor decided to transfer to [[Saint Joseph's Hawks men's basketball|Saint Joseph's]].<ref name=nba />\n\n===College statistics===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[1997\u201398 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1997\u201398]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[1997\u201398 Villanova Wildcats men's basketball team|Villanova]]\n| 21 || 5 ||  || .354 || .217 || .357 || 1.7 || 1.2 || 0.5 || 0.0 || 4.7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1998\u201399 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1998\u201399]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1998\u201399 Saint Joseph's Hawks men's basketball team|Saint Joseph's]]\n| colspan=11 align=center | ''Did not play \u2013 transfer''\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[1999\u20132000 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|1999\u201300]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[1999\u20132000 Saint Joseph's Hawks men's basketball team|Saint Joseph's]]\n| 28 || 28 || 31.5 || .408 || .354 || '''.736''' || '''4.4''' || '''2.6''' || '''1.1''' || '''0.1''' || 16.6\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[2000\u201301 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2000\u201301]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[2000\u201301 Saint Joseph's Hawks men's basketball team|Saint Joseph's]]\n| '''32''' || '''32''' || '''33.5''' || '''.465''' || '''.374''' || .676 || 3.7 || '''2.6''' || '''1.1''' || 0.0 || '''22.1'''\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[2001\u201302 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2001\u201302]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[2001\u201302 Saint Joseph's Hawks men's basketball team|Saint Joseph's]]\n| 29 || 29 || 33.0 || .429 || .286 || .717 || 4.2 || 2.5 || 0.6 || 0.0 || 17.5\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | '''Career'''\n| align=\"left\" |\n| 110 || 94 ||  || .430 || .331 || .692 || 3.6 || 2.3 || 0.9 || 0.0 || 16.1\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.proballers.com/basketball/player/7022/marvin-o-connor Career stats at ProBallers.com]\n*[https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Marvin-OConnor/Summary/4774 Profile at RealGM.com]\n*[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/marvin-oconnor-1.html College stats at Sports-Reference.com]\n*[https://www.basketball-reference.com/international/players/marvin-oconnor-1.html International stats at Basketball-Reference.com]\n\n{{Robert V. Geasey Trophy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:O'Connor, Marvin}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Serbia]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:KK Partizan players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Saint Joseph's Hawks men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Villanova Wildcats men's basketball players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Under construction}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name         