}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| TBA\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| TBA\n|-\n| ''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | June 3, 1983\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| $5,000,000<ref name=\"pshchomovies\">{{Cite web | url = http://www.thepsychomovies.com/films/psycho2/ | title = Psycho II | website = The Psycho Movies | accessdate = June 30, 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130603054014/http://www.thepsychomovies.com/films/psycho2/ | archivedate = June 3, 2013 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| $34,725,000<ref name=\"pshchomovies\">{{Cite web | url = http://www.thepsychomovies.com/films/psycho2/ | title = Psycho II | website = The Psycho Movies | accessdate = June 30, 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130603054014/http://www.thepsychomovies.com/films/psycho2/ | archivedate = June 3, 2013 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| TBA\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| TBA\n|-\n| ''[[Psycho III]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | July 2, 1986\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| $8,400,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Film/57450-PSYCHO-III?sid=aafcd0f8-47d7-4096-a3ad-d7a6e27ed3fb&sr=0.11734072&cp=1&pos=4|title=AFI&#124;Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| $14,481,606<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Film/57450-PSYCHO-III?sid=aafcd0f8-47d7-4096-a3ad-d7a6e27ed3fb&sr=0.11734072&cp=1&pos=4|title=AFI&#124;Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| TBA\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| TBA\n|-\n| ''[[Bates Motel (film)|Bates Motel]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | July 5, 1987\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| TBA\n| colspan=\"3\" |  {{Hs|$0}}\u2014 Television film \u2014\n|-\n| ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | November 10, 1990\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| TBA\n| colspan=\"3\" |  {{Hs|$0}}\u2014 Television film \u2014\n|-\n| ''[[Psycho (1998 film)|Psycho]]''\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | December 4, 1998\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| $60,000,000<ref name=\"mojo\">{{mojo title|id=psycho98|title=Psycho (1998)}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| $21,485,655<ref name=\"mojo\">{{mojo title|id=psycho98|title=Psycho (1998)}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| $15,685,000<ref name=\"mojo\">{{mojo title|id=psycho98|title=Psycho (1998)}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| $37,170,655<ref name=\"mojo\">{{mojo title|id=psycho98|title=Psycho (1998)}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Total\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| TBA\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| TBA\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| TBA\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| TBA\n|}\n\n===Critical and public response===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n! Film\n! Year\n! [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! [[Metacritic]]\n! Gross\n! Release date\n! Running time\n|-\n| ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]''\n| 1960\n| 96% (95 reviews)<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/psycho/ </ref>\n| 97 (17 reviews)<ref>https://www.metacritic.com/movie/psycho-1960 </ref>\n| $50,000,000\n| June 16, 1960\n| 109 minutes\n|-\n| ''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]''\n| 1983\n| 59% (34 reviews)<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/psycho_2/ </ref>\n| 54 (13 reviews)<ref>https://www.metacritic.com/movie/psycho-ii </ref>\n| $34,725,000<ref name=\"mojo-p2\">http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=psycho2.htm  </ref>\n| June 3, 1983\n| 113 minutes\n|-\n| ''[[Psycho III]]''\n| 1986\n| 58% (19 reviews)<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/psycho_3/ </ref>\n| 58 (13 reviews)<ref>https://www.metacritic.com/movie/psycho-iii </ref>\n| $14,481,606<ref name=\"mojo-p3\" />\n| July 2, 1986\n| 94 minutes\n|-\n| ''[[Bates Motel (film)|Bates Motel]]''\n| 1987\n| N/A<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/bates-motel/  </ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| July 5, 1987\n| 90 minutes\n|-\n| ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]''\n| 1990\n| N/A (2 critics)<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/psycho_4_the_beginning/ </ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| November 10, 1990\n| 96 minutes\n|-\n| ''[[Psycho (1998 film)|Psycho]]''\n| 1998\n| 38% (78 reviews)<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1084964-psycho/ </ref>\n| 47 (23 reviews)<ref>https://www.metacritic.com/movie/psycho </ref>\n| $21,456,130<ref name=\"mojo-p1998\" />\n| December 4, 1998\n| 104 minutes\n|}\n\n===Accolades===\nIn 1960, ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' received four [[Academy Award]] nominations including Best Director for [[Alfred Hitchcock]], Best Supporting Actress for [[Janet Leigh]], Best Cinematography and Best Art Direction. All three sequels have been nominated for Saturn Awards. ''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]'' received a nomination for Best Screenplay for writer [[Tom Holland (director)|Tom Holland]]. ''[[Psycho III]]'' was nominated for Best Horror Film. ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]'' was nominated for Best Genre Television Series.\n\n===Legacy===\n''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' has become one of the most recognizable films ever made. The shower scene alone has become one of the most iconic cut scenes in cinematic history. ''Psycho'' is frequently referenced, given homage to or spoofed in television shows such as ''[[The Simpsons]]'', ''[[South Park]]'', ''[[American Dad!]]'', ''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]'' and more. Films such as ''[[Scream 2]]'', ''[[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|Charlie and the Chocolate Factory]]'', ''[[Throw Momma from the Train]]'', ''[[Scary Movie]]'' and more have referenced the film. Many critics and filmmakers have cited ''Psycho'' as the film that modernized the horror genre. Horror writer David. J. Schow stated (in ''[[The Psycho Legacy]]'') \"It brought the idea that the killer in a horror film was not a mutant, didn't have dents in his head; he could look like that nice young boy from next door\". The film also brought in a new level of acceptable violence and sexuality in movies. Both [[Anthony Perkins]] and [[Janet Leigh]] spent the rest of their careers being typecasted by the film. Even [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s films began to decline in critical and financial popularity after the release of ''Psycho''. Hitchcock film scholars argue that for the rest of his career, Hitchcock's films were constantly being compared to ''Psycho''. The \"Psycho\" films still maintain a very large fanbase. Various websites dedicated to the franchise such as ''The Psycho Movies.com'' have appeared on the Internet. Books detailing the making and impact of the film such as ''Alfred Hitchcock and The Making of Psycho'', ''The Moment of Psycho'', Janet Leigh's ''Psycho: Behind The Scenes of the Classic Thriller'' have been published over the years. Two retrospective documentaries have been released detailing the making of all four films including ''The Making of Psycho'' (1997) and ''[[The Psycho Legacy]]'' (2010). The film also spawned the show ''[[Alfred Hitchcock: The Art of Making Movies]]'' at [[Universal Studios Florida]], with part of the show detailing how the shower scene was filmed. In 1992, ''Psycho'' was added to the [[National Film Registry]] by the [[Library of Congress]].\n\nA musical stage adaptation was performed January-February 2019 at PULP Black Box Theatre in Atlanta, GA. <ref>https://www.facebook.com/events/1973956552682770/</ref>\n\n==Other media and merchandise==\n\nVarious ''Psycho'' related merchandise has been sold ever since the release of the original film. Merchandise includes T-shirts, posters, DVDs, books, stationery, shot glasses, shower curtains, action figures, model house kits, pens and more. Much of the merchandise is related to the fictional Bates Motel where items commonly found in an actual motel have the Bates Motel logo on them. A Bates Motel light up sign was released in 2009. To coincide with the 50th anniversary of the release of the original film, a Psycho house model kit was released in the U.S. Props from all the films are also sold occasionally on [[eBay]]. The original one sheet poster for ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' is worth around $3000 in mint condition. The original one sheets for ''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]'', ''[[Psycho III]]'' and ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]'' are worth around $50 each.\n\n===Graphic novels===\nIn 1992, a series of [[graphic novel]]s based on the original ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' was published by the Innovation Comics group. Today, the novels are out of print and are very rare to find.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n===The ''Psycho'' House and Bates Motel sets===\nThe Bates House and Motel were constructed on the backlot at Universal City Studios in 1959 for the production of ''Psycho''. It has been said that the house, designed by art director's Joseph Hurley and Robert Clathworthy, was loosely based on an Edward Hopper painting called \"House by the Railroad\". The house and motel sets were actually empty shells, also known as facades. When the house was originally built, there was no right side of the house, since the right side is never seen on camera in the original ''Psycho'' film. Interiors of the Bates house and motel were constructed on Sound stage 18-A at Universal, just a short walk from the actual exterior locations making production convenient for all involved. After production had wrapped on ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'', the house was featured in several television productions including ''The Virginian'' and ''Boris Karloff's Mystery Theater''.\n\nIn 1964, Universal Studios opened its patented Studio Tram Tour. The right side of the house was then added and the set was unceremoniously dubbed \"The Psycho House\". The house and even the motel went on to appear in several shows such as ''[[Night Gallery]]'', ''[[The Hardy Boys]]'' and even in films such as ''[[Invitation to a Gunfighter]]'' and ''[[Modern Problems]]''. The motel was torn down in 1979 and the house was moved to an alternate location on the backlot to accommodate the new tour. In 1982, Richard Franklin and Hilton A. Green announced plans to film ''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]''. The house was then moved to a location that best matched the original hill and only about 40 feet of the motel was actually re-built. The rest of the motel in the film was a matte painting. TV shows during the '80s promoted the Universal Tour and prominently featured the Psycho House including ''[[Amazing Stories]]'', ''[[Knight Rider (1982 TV series)|Knight Rider]]'', ''[[Welcome to My Nightmare]]'', and ''[[Diff'rent Strokes]]''.\n\nIn 1985, the Bates Motel was fully re-built for the filming of ''[[Psycho III]]''. In 1987, the NBC-TV network announced plans for the TV pilot ''[[Bates Motel (film)|Bates Motel]]''. The motel in the film was re-modeled to look very Spanish like. This version of the set remained until 1994 when the new renovations were taken away and the motel was put back to look the way it did in the original Psycho. An episode of ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'' from the early 1990s featured the Psycho House and Bates Motel as key locations in the popular Angela Lansbury series.\n\nIn 1988, plans for ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]'' were underway at Universal. Plans to shoot the movie in Orlando, Florida were set into motion and the film crew constructed a full-scale replica of the Bates Motel and Psycho House at the soon-to-be built Universal Studios Florida. The final dressing and painting was done by the Psycho IV art department crew in 1990, but the house and motel was fully built in 1988 long before the production team was assembled for the project. After production wrapped, the sets were left as attractions at the park until 1999 when it was torn down to make room for another attraction.\n\nIn 1998, the Psycho House in California was renovated to preserve the set. All of the rotting wood was replaced and the set had a new paint job. That same year, plans to remake ''Psycho'' were announced. It was originally announced that Gus Van Sant was going to be using the original house and motel sets. However, the production team built a new house directly in front of the old one, and the motel was updated to look like it was from the 1960s. The new house was moved next to the original house and remained there for about three years after production. In 2003, due to popular demand, the remake's house was torn down and the motel was restored to the original way once again. To this day, the house and motel are still standing on the backlot of Universal and continue to be major tourist attractions. The [[Studio Tour|tram tour]] features an actor playing Norman Bates coming out of cabin 1 with a body, putting it in the trunk of a car and then wielding a large knife at the tourists as the tram drives away.\n\n===''24 Hour Psycho''===\nAn art installation, ''[[24 Hour Psycho]]'', created by artist [[Douglas Gordon]] in 1993, and later installed in the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in New York, consists of a silent screening of ''Psycho'', slowed down to two frames per second (from the usual 24), so that it lasts 24 hours rather than 109 minutes. ''24 Hour Psycho'' is featured prominently in [[Don DeLillo]]'s 2010 novel ''[[Point Omega]]''.\n\n===''The Psycho Legacy'' (2010)===\n{{Main|The Psycho Legacy}}\nIn 2010, a direct-to-DVD documentary was released called ''The Psycho Legacy''. It included interviews with cast and crew from all four Psycho films. It also featured interviews with current horror filmmakers who are fans of the series. The documentary was written, produced and directed by horror journalist Robert Galluzzo. Galluzo made the documentary because of the lack of information on the sequels and also to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the release of the original film. The documentary discussed the impact and legacy of the original ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' and the production stories of ''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]'', ''[[Psycho III]]'' and ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]''. To the surprise of some critics and fans, the failed TV pilot ''[[Bates Motel (film)|Bates Motel]]'' and the [[Gus Van Sant]] [[Psycho (1998 film)|remake]] were not discussed in the documentary, however originally in the deleted scenes section on the DVD two short segments on the two films were supposed to be on there, however for unknown reasons they were left off of the DVD when it was released. The documentary sold well, received mostly positive reviews and garnered new interest in the series from horror fans.\n\n===''Hitchcock'' (2012)===\n{{Main|Hitchcock (film)}}\nOn April 13, 2012, production started on a film adaptation of [[Stephen Rebello]]'s non-fiction book ''[[Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho]]'', which follows the complex relationship between [[Alfred Hitchcock]] and wife [[Alma Reville]] during the filming of ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' in 1959. The film is directed by [[Sacha Gervasi]] and stars [[Anthony Hopkins]] as director Alfred Hitchcock, Helen Mirren as his wife [[Alma Reville]], [[Scarlett Johansson]] as [[Janet Leigh]], [[Jessica Biel]] as [[Vera Miles]], and [[James D'Arcy]] as [[Anthony Perkins]]. Produced by [[The Montecito Picture Company]] and distributed by [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]], the film was released on November 23, 2012 in selected cities with a worldwide release on December 14, 2012. The film has received mixed reviews from critics and moderate box office returns, with a worldwide gross of $5,337,378 as of January 3, 2013.\n\n===2017 documentary: \"78/52\"===\n\nA documentary on the production of ''Psycho'' was released on Oct 13, 2017 by director Alexandre O. Philippe running 91 minutes. The cast of participants included Guillermo del Toro, Peter Bogdanovich, Bret Easton Ellis, Jamie Lee Curtis, Karyn Kusama, Eli Roth, Oz Perkins, Leigh Whannell, Walter Murch, Danny Elfman, Elijah Wood, Richard Stanley, and Neil Marshall.<ref>. {{cite web | date = January 24, 2017 | author = Owen Gleiberman | url = https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/7852-review-psycho-1201966555/ | title = Film Review: \u201878/52: Hitchcock\u2019s Shower Scene\u2019 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety Magazine]] }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [[Janet Leigh|Leigh, Janet]]; Nickens, Christopher (1995). ''Psycho: Behind the Scenes of the Classic Thriller''. Harmony Press.\n* {{Cite book| last=Rebello|first=Stephen|authorlink=Stephen Rebello|year=1990|title=Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho|publisher=Marion Boyars|isbn=0-7145-3003-4|ref=harv }}\n* {{Cite book |last=Reavill |first=Gil |year=2007 |title=Aftermath, Inc.: Cleaning Up After CSI Goes Home |publisher=Gotham |isbn=978-1-59240-296-0 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781592402960 }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thepsychomovies.com The Psycho Movies] \u2013 A comprehensive site for the film series\n{{Psycho}}\n\n[[Category:American film series]]\n[[Category:Film series introduced in 1960]]\n[[Category:Films about psychopaths]]\n[[Category:Horror media franchises]]\n[[Category:Media franchises introduced in 1959]]\n[[Category:Psycho (franchise)| ]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilms", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psycho_(franchise)"}
{"title_page": "Wisconsin Highway 77", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n|state=WI\n|type=WI\n|route=77\n|length_mi=139.94\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=\n<ref name=\"WH1\">{{cite web | last = Bessert | first = Chris | title =Wisconsin Highways: Highways 70-79 (Highway 77) | work =Wisconsin Highways | url =http://www.wisconsinhighways.org/listings/WiscHwys70-79.html#STH-077 | accessdate = 2007-03-20}}</ref>\n|direction_a=West\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=MN|MN|48}} in [[Danbury, Wisconsin|Danbury]]\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=MI|US-Bus|2|dab1=Ironwood}} in Hurley\n|previous_type=WI\n|next_type=WI\n|previous_route=76\n|next_route=78\n|counties=[[Burnett County, Wisconsin|Burnett]], [[Washburn County, Wisconsin|Washburn]], [[Sawyer County, Wisconsin|Sawyer]], [[Ashland County, Wisconsin|Ashland]], [[Iron County, Wisconsin|Iron]]\n|junction={{Jct|state=WI|WI|35}} in Danbury<br>{{Jct|state=WI|US|53}} in [[Minong, Wisconsin|Minong]]<br>{{Jct|state=WI|US|63|WI|27}} in [[Hayward, Wisconsin|Hayward]]<br>{{Jct|state=WI|WI|13}} in [[Mellen, Wisconsin|Mellen]]<br>{{Jct|state=WI|WI|122}} in [[Upson, Wisconsin|Upson]]<br>{{Jct|state=WI|US|51}} in [[Hurley, Wisconsin|Hurley]]\n}}\n'''State Trunk Highway 77''' (often called '''Highway 77''', '''STH 77''' or '''WIS 77''') is a [[state highway (US)|state highway]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Wisconsin]]. It runs east&ndash;west in northwest Wisconsin from the Michigan border in [[Hurley, Wisconsin|Hurley]] to the Minnesota border near [[Danbury, Wisconsin|Danbury]]. The highway was first designated in 1920 and was extended to the current routing sometime between 1948 and 1956.\n\n==Route description==\n[[File:WIS 77 East Terminus Looking West.jpg|thumb|right|Eastern terminus in Hurley]]\nThe highway begins at the [[Minnesota]] state line along the [[St. Croix River (Wisconsin-Minnesota)|St. Croix River]] as a continuation of [[Minnesota State Highway 48|MIN 48]] and runs east from it. The highway passes by County Trunk Highway (CTH) F in [[Danbury, Wisconsin|Danbury]] and begins a [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]] with [[Wisconsin Highway 35|WIS 35]] in the east of Danbury. The concurrency runs northeastward along the St. Croix River until the highway leaves the concurrency and runs eastward from it. The highway passes by a large amount of lakes and then curves to the north, meeting [[U.S. Route 53|US 53]] and its business route in [[Minong, Wisconsin|Minong]]. It then runs east from it, intersecting with CTH-G. Between CTH-G and CTH-M, the highway runs southeast and crosses a railroad. The highway then runs eastward towards a concurrency with [[Wisconsin Highway 27|WIS 27]].<ref name=gmaps/>\n\nAfter its concurrency with WIS 27 starts, the highway meets Smith Lake and curves to the south, running towards [[Hayward, Wisconsin|Hayward]]. After entering Hayward, it meets [[U.S. Route 63|US 63]] and WIS 27 follows it, ending its concurrency with the highway. After intersecting with US 63, the highway runs north of Hayward Lake. East of Hayward, the highway runs northeastward. It passes to the northwest of Round Lake and runs around the west and north of McClaine Lake, and then runs east from it. The highway then enters the [[Chequamegon-Nicolet National Forest]] and passes by more lakes in the National Forest, running northeastward to [[Clam Lake, Wisconsin|Clam Lake]]. From there, the highway runs east.<ref name=gmaps/>\n\nSoon after the highway exits the National Forest, it begins a concurrency with [[Wisconsin Highway 13|WIS 13]] and runs northward towards [[Mellen, Wisconsin|Mellen]], and runs through another section of the National Forest. The highway enters Mellen along Main Street and exits the concurrency, running along Lake Drive before running east from Lake Drive just north of Tannery Town. The highway then runs east-northeast along a railroad, passing through [[Tyler Forks, Wisconsin|Tyler Forks]], [[Rouse, Wisconsin|Rouse]], and [[Upson, Wisconsin|Upson]], where it meets [[Wisconsin Highway 122|WIS 122]]. The highway continues to follow the railroad before it ends, at which point the highway enters [[Hurley, Wisconsin|Hurley]] and terminates at [[U.S. Route 51 in Wisconsin|US 51]] west of the [[Michigan]] state line along the Montreal River.<ref name=gmaps/>\n\n==History==\n\nThe highway was first designated between Mellen to Hurley in northeast Wisconsin.<ref name=\"1920map\">{{cite map |author1 = Rand McNally & Co. |year = 1920 |title = Rand McNally Official 1920 Auto Trails Map |map = District No. 8: Wisconsin, Northern Ill., Northern Mich. |map-url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/maps/id/1100/rec/75 |scale = [c. 1:877,824] |location = Chicago |publisher = Rand McNally & Co. |oclc = 712305940 |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 12, 2020 }}</ref> In 1922, a highway linking Minong and Hayward, to be designated WIS&nbsp;124, was constructed,<ref name=\"1922map\">{{cite map |author1 = Rand McNally & Co. |year = 1922 |title = Rand McNally Official 1922 Auto Trails Map |map = District No. 8: Wisconsin, Northern Ill., Northern Mich. |map-url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/maps/id/14541/rec/76 |scale = c. 1:696,960 |location = Chicago |publisher = Rand McNally & Co. |oclc = 664138250 |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 12, 2020 }}</ref> and it was open by 1923.<ref name=\"1923map\">{{cite map |author1 = Wisconsin Motorists Association |year = 1923 |title = Our Own Map of Wisconsin |url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/maps/id/15960/rec/65 |scale = Scale not given |location = Milwaukee |publisher = Wisconsin Motorists Association |oclc = 318360666 |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 12, 2020 }}</ref> In 1924, the highway was extended west to Hayward and the section west of WIS 35 was designated was WIS 152.<ref name=\"1924map\">{{cite map |author1 = Wisconsin Motorists Association |year = c. 1924 |title = Our Map of Wisconsin |url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/maps/id/14655/rec/63 |scale = Scale not given |location = Milwaukee |publisher = Wisconsin Motorists Association |oclc = 664274042  |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 12, 2020 }}</ref> Sometime between 1948 and 1956, the highway was extended west to the Minnesota state line. The former WIS 124 (by then WIS 27) and WIS 152 were redesignated as parts of the highway.<ref name=\"1948map\">{{cite map |author1 = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |title = Preliminary Traffic Map, Showing Annual 24 Hour Average Traffic, State of Wisconsin |url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/maps/id/14173/rec/69 |scale = [c. 1:1,198,000] |location = Madison |publisher = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |oclc = 770711221 |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 12, 2020 |date = 1948 }}</ref><ref name=\"1956maps\">{{cite web |author1 = Wisconsin Highway Commission |year = 1956 |title = Wisconsin State Atlas 1956 Highway Maps |url = http://www.historicmapworks.com/Atlas/US/9643/Wisconsin+State+Atlas+1956+Highway+Maps/ |location = Madison |publisher = Wisconsin Highway Commission |via = Historic Map Works |access-date = April 12, 2020 }}</ref> In 1956, the only section that was not part of a concurrency that was paved was near the eastern terminus in Hurley.<ref name=1956maps/>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{Jcttop|length_ref=<ref name=gmaps>{{google maps |url = https://www.google.com/maps/dir/46.0125865,-92.443927/46.0999445,-91.8374741/46.100362,-91.827588/46.0556007,-91.5094779/46.01867,-91.4758838/46.3668892,-90.4076381/46.4498692,-90.1818159/@46.2393101,-91.9282531,9z/am=t/data=!4m19!4m18!1m0!1m0!1m0!1m0!1m10!3m4!1m2!1d-90.6797901!2d46.2523404!3s0x52a97eef0890dd21:0xc83db758178bef5c!3m4!1m2!1d-90.6590246!2d46.3248408!3s0x52a97859d42d178f:0xdd68822e35d897a4!1m0!1m0!3e0 |title = Length and Route of WIS&nbsp;77 |access-date = April 12, 2020 }}</ref>}}\n{{WIint\n|county=Burnett\n|cspan=3\n|location=Swiss\n|lspan=3\n|mile=0.0\n|road={{jct|state=WI|MN|48}}\n|notes=[[Minnesota]] state line\n}}\n{{WIint\n|type=concur\n|mile=4.0\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|35|dir1=south}}\n|notes=Southern end of WIS 35 concurrency\n}}\n{{WIint\n|mile=6.2\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|35|dir1=north}}\n|notes=Northern end of WIS 35 concurrency\n}}\n{{WIint\n|county=Washburn\n|cspan=2\n|location=Minong\n|lspan=2\n|mile=33.1\n|road={{jct|state=WI|US|53}}\n|notes=Interchange\n}}\n{{WIint\n|mile=33.6\n|road={{jct|state=WI|US-Bus|53|dab1=Minong}}\n}}\n{{WIint\n|type=concur\n|county=Sawyer\n|cspan=2\n|location=Lenroot\n|mile=50.5\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|27|dir1=north}}\n|notes=Northern end of WIS 27 concurrency\n}}\n{{WIint\n|location=Hayward\n|mile=54.1\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=WI|US|63|WI|27|dir2=south}}\n|notes=Southern end of WIS 27 concurrency\n}}\n{{WIint\n|type=concur\n|county=Ashland\n|cspan=2\n|location=Morse\n|mile=100.5\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|13|dir1=south}}\n|notes=Southern end of WIS 13 concurrency\n}}\n{{WIint\n|location=Mellen\n|mile=113.6\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|13|dir1=north}}\n|notes=Northern end of WIS 13 concurrency\n}}\n{{WIint\n|county=Iron\n|cspan=2\n|location=Anderson\n|ctdab=Iron\n|mile=126.9\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|122|dir1=north}}\n}}\n{{WIint\n|location=Hurley\n|mile=139.5\n|road={{jct|state=WI|US|51}}\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Wisconsin Highway 77}}\n\n[[Category:State highways in Wisconsin|077]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Washburn County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Sawyer County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Ashland County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Iron County, Wisconsin]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road\n|state=WI\n|type=WI\n|route=77\n|length_mi=139.94\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=\n<ref name=\"WH1\">{{cite web | last = Bessert | first = Chris | title =Wisconsin Highways: Highways 70-79 (Highway 77) | work =Wisconsin Highways | url =http://www.wisconsinhighways.org/listings/WiscHwys70-79.html#STH-077 | accessdate = 2007-03-20}}</ref>\n|direction_a=West\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=MN|MN|48}} in [[Danbury, Wisconsin|Danbury]]\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=MI|US-Bus|2|dab1=Ironwood}} in Hurley\n|previous_type=WI\n|next_type=WI\n|previous_route=76\n|next_route=78\n|counties=[[Burnett County, Wisconsin|Burnett]], [[Washburn County, Wisconsin|Washburn]], [[Sawyer County, Wisconsin|Sawyer]], [[Ashland County, Wisconsin|Ashland]], [[Iron County, Wisconsin|Iron]]\n|junction={{Jct|state=WI|WI|35}} in Danbury<br>{{Jct|state=WI|US|53}} in [[Minong, Wisconsin|Minong]]<br>{{Jct|state=WI|US|63|WI|27}} in [[Hayward, Wisconsin|Hayward]]<br>{{Jct|state=WI|WI|13}} in [[Mellen, Wisconsin|Mellen]]<br>{{Jct|state=WI|WI|122}} in [[Upson, Wisconsin|Upson]]<br>{{Jct|state=WI|US|51}} in [[Hurley, Wisconsin|Hurley]]\n}}\n'''State Trunk Highway 77''' (often called '''Highway 77''', '''STH 77''' or '''WIS 77''') is a [[state highway (US)|state highway]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Wisconsin]]. It runs east&ndash;west in northwest Wisconsin from the Michigan border in [[Hurley, Wisconsin|Hurley]] to the Minnesota border near [[Danbury, Wisconsin|Danbury]]. The highway was first designated in 1920 and was extended to the current routing sometime between 1948 and 1956.\n\n==Route description==\n[[File:WIS 77 East Terminus Looking West.jpg|thumb|right|Eastern terminus in Hurley]]\nThe highway begins at the [[Minnesota]] state line along the [[St. Croix River (Wisconsin-Minnesota)|St. Croix River]] as a continuation of [[Minnesota State Highway 48|MIN 48]] and runs east from it. The highway passes by County Trunk Highway (CTH) F in [[Danbury, Wisconsin|Danbury]] and begins a [[concurrency (road)|concurrency]] with [[Wisconsin Highway 35|WIS 35]] in the east of Danbury. The concurrency runs northeastward along the St. Croix River until the highway leaves the concurrency and runs eastward from it. The highway passes by a large amount of lakes and then curves to the north, meeting [[U.S. Route 53|US 53]] and its business route in [[Minong, Wisconsin|Minong]]. It then runs east from it, intersecting with CTH-G. Between CTH-G and CTH-M, the highway runs southeast and crosses a railroad. The highway then runs eastward towards a concurrency with [[Wisconsin Highway 27|WIS 27]].<ref name=gmaps/>\n\nAfter its concurrency with WIS 27 starts, the highway meets Smith Lake and curves to the south, running towards [[Hayward, Wisconsin|Hayward]]. After entering Hayward, it meets [[U.S. Route 63|US 63]] and WIS 27 follows it, ending its concurrency with the highway. After intersecting with US 63, the highway runs north of Hayward Lake. East of Hayward, the highway runs northeastward. It passes to the northwest of Round Lake and runs around the west and north of McClaine Lake, and then runs east from it. The highway then enters the [[Chequamegon-Nicolet National Forest]] and passes by more lakes in the National Forest, running northeastward to [[Clam Lake, Wisconsin|Clam Lake]]. From there, the highway runs east.<ref name=gmaps/>\n\nSoon after the highway exits the National Forest, it begins a concurrency with [[Wisconsin Highway 13|WIS 13]] and runs northward towards [[Mellen, Wisconsin|Mellen]], and runs through another section of the National Forest. The highway enters Mellen along Main Street and exits the concurrency, running along Lake Drive before running east from Lake Drive just north of Tannery Town. The highway then runs east-northeast along a railroad, passing through [[Tyler Forks, Wisconsin|Tyler Forks]], [[Rouse, Wisconsin|Rouse]], and [[Upson, Wisconsin|Upson]], where it meets [[Wisconsin Highway 122|WIS 122]]. The highway continues to follow the railroad before it ends, at which point the highway enters [[Hurley, Wisconsin|Hurley]] and terminates at [[U.S. Route 51 in Wisconsin|US 51]] west of the [[Michigan]] state line along the Montreal River.<ref name=gmaps/>\n\n==History==\n\nThe highway was first designated between Mellen to Hurley in northeast Wisconsin.<ref name=\"1920map\">{{cite map |author1 = Rand McNally & Co. |year = 1920 |title = Rand McNally Official 1920 Auto Trails Map |map = District No. 8: Wisconsin, Northern Ill., Northern Mich. |map-url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/maps/id/1100/rec/75 |scale = [c. 1:877,824] |location = Chicago |publisher = Rand McNally & Co. |oclc = 712305940 |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 12, 2020 }}</ref> In 1922, a highway linking Minong and Hayward, to be designated WIS&nbsp;124, was constructed,<ref name=\"1922map\">{{cite map |author1 = Rand McNally & Co. |year = 1922 |title = Rand McNally Official 1922 Auto Trails Map |map = District No. 8: Wisconsin, Northern Ill., Northern Mich. |map-url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/maps/id/14541/rec/76 |scale = c. 1:696,960 |location = Chicago |publisher = Rand McNally & Co. |oclc = 664138250 |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 12, 2020 }}</ref> and it was open by 1923.<ref name=\"1923map\">{{cite map |author1 = Wisconsin Motorists Association |year = 1923 |title = Our Own Map of Wisconsin |url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/maps/id/15960/rec/65 |scale = Scale not given |location = Milwaukee |publisher = Wisconsin Motorists Association |oclc = 318360666 |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 12, 2020 }}</ref> In 1924, the highway was extended west to Hayward and the section west of WIS 35 was designated was WIS 152.<ref name=\"1924map\">{{cite map |author1 = Wisconsin Motorists Association |year = c. 1924 |title = Our Map of Wisconsin |url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/maps/id/14655/rec/63 |scale = Scale not given |location = Milwaukee |publisher = Wisconsin Motorists Association |oclc = 664274042  |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 12, 2020 }}</ref> Sometime between 1948 and 1956, the highway was extended west to the Minnesota state line. The former WIS 124 (by then WIS 27) and WIS 152 were redesignated as parts of the highway.<ref name=\"1948map\">{{cite map |author1 = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |title = Preliminary Traffic Map, Showing Annual 24 Hour Average Traffic, State of Wisconsin |url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/maps/id/14173/rec/69 |scale = [c. 1:1,198,000] |location = Madison |publisher = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |oclc = 770711221 |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 12, 2020 |date = 1948 }}</ref><ref name=\"1956maps\">{{cite web |author1 = Wisconsin Highway Commission |year = 1956 |title = Wisconsin State Atlas 1956 Highway Maps |url = http://www.historicmapworks.com/Atlas/US/9643/Wisconsin+State+Atlas+1956+Highway+Maps/ |location = Madison |publisher = Wisconsin Highway Commission |via = Historic Map Works |access-date = April 12, 2020 }}</ref> In 1956, the only section that was not part of a concurrency that was paved was near the eastern terminus in Hurley.<ref name=1956maps/>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{Jcttop|length_ref=<ref name=gmaps>{{google maps |url = https://www.google.com/maps/dir/46.0125865,-92.443927/46.0999445,-91.8374741/46.100362,-91.827588/46.0556007,-91.5094779/46.01867,-91.4758838/46.3668892,-90.4076381/46.4498692,-90.1818159/@46.2393101,-91.9282531,9z/am=t/data=!4m19!4m18!1m0!1m0!1m0!1m0!1m10!3m4!1m2!1d-90.6797901!2d46.2523404!3s0x52a97eef0890dd21:0xc83db758178bef5c!3m4!1m2!1d-90.6590246!2d46.3248408!3s0x52a97859d42d178f:0xdd68822e35d897a4!1m0!1m0!3e0 |title = Length and Route of WIS&nbsp;77 |access-date = April 12, 2020 }}</ref>}}\n{{WIint\n|county=Burnett\n|cspan=3\n|location=Swiss\n|lspan=3\n|mile=0.0\n|road={{jct|state=WI|MN|48}}\n|notes=[[Minnesota]] state line\n}}\n{{WIint\n|type=concur\n|mile=4.0\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|35|dir1=south}}\n|notes=Southern end of WIS 35 concurrency\n}}\n{{WIint\n|mile=6.2\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|35|dir1=north}}\n|notes=Northern end of WIS 35 concurrency\n}}\n{{WIint\n|county=Washburn\n|cspan=2\n|location=Minong\n|lspan=2\n|mile=33.1\n|road={{jct|state=WI|US|53}}\n|notes=Interchange\n}}\n{{WIint\n|mile=33.6\n|road={{jct|state=WI|US-Bus|53|dab1=Minong}}\n}}\n{{WIint\n|type=concur\n|county=Sawyer\n|cspan=2\n|location=Lenroot\n|mile=50.5\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|27|dir1=north}}\n|notes=Northern end of WIS 27 concurrency\n}}\n{{WIint\n|location=Hayward\n|mile=54.1\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=WI|US|63|WI|27|dir2=south}}\n|notes=Southern end of WIS 27 concurrency\n}}\n{{WIint\n|type=concur\n|county=Ashland\n|cspan=2\n|location=Morse\n|mile=100.5\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|13|dir1=south}}\n|notes=Southern end of WIS 13 concurrency\n}}\n{{WIint\n|location=Mellen\n|mile=113.6\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|13|dir1=north}}\n|notes=Northern end of WIS 13 concurrency\n}}\n{{WIint\n|county=Iron\n|cspan=2\n|location=Anderson\n|ctdab=Iron\n|mile=126.9\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|122|dir1=north}}\n}}\n{{WIint\n|location=Hurley\n|mile=139.5\n|road={{jct|state=WI|US|51}}\n}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Wisconsin Highway 77}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:State highways in Wisconsin|077]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Washburn County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Sawyer County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Ashland County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Iron County, Wisconsin]]\n", "name_user": "Imzadi1979", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:split out EL", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wisconsin_Highway_77"}
{"title_page": "Bernard Hughes", "text_new": "'''Bernard Hughes''' (1808-1878) was an [[Irish people|Irish]] nineteenth century industrialist and politician.\n\nHe was born in Co. Armagh but moved to [[Belfast]] in 1826. Over a period of 40 years he built up the largest baking and milling industry in Ireland. His continuing fame is due to his development and production of cheap and wholesome bread. The most famous item was the ''Belfast Bap'', more commonly known as ''Barney's Baps''. His bread is recalled in the rhyme:\n:''Barney Hughes' bread''\n:''Sticks to your belly like lead.''\nHis main mill was located in Divis Street in the lower [[Falls Road, Belfast|Falls Road]].<ref>{{cite web |title=1884 Hungarian Flour Mill |url=http://archiseek.com/2017/1884-hungarian-flour-mills-divis-street-belfast/ |website=Archiseek |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe was the first Catholic elected to [[Belfast Corporation]]. He campaigned against sectarianism and for social justice.  He gave evidence to the Royal Commission of Inquiry into the sectarian riots of 1857 and 1864 which angered the Tory establishment in the city. Although he was sometimes in conflict with the Catholic church he gave land for the building of [[St. Peter's Cathedral, Belfast|St Peter's Cathedral]] in the Lower Falls area <ref>{{cite book |last1=Magee |first1=Jack |title=Barney: Bernard Hughes of Belfast |date=2001 |publisher=Ulster Historical Foundation |location=Belfast |isbn=1903688051 |pages=285}}</ref>\n\nHe is buried in ''Friar's Bush Graveyard'' - the oldest cemetery in Belfast.<ref>{{cite web |title=Friar's Bush |url=http://www.belfastcity.gov.uk/community/cemeteries/friarsbush.aspx |website=Belfast City Council |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hughes, Bernard}}\n[[Category:People from Belfast]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Belfast]]\n[[Category:Members of Belfast City Council]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:People from County Armagh]]\n[[Category:Irish philanthropists]]\n[[Category:1808 births]]\n[[Category:1878 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''Bernard Hughes''' (1808-1878) was an [[Irish people|Irish]] nineteenth century industrialist and politician.\n\nHe was born in Co. Armagh but moved to [[Belfast]] in 1826. Over a period of 40 years he built up the largest baking and milling industry in Ireland. His continuing fame is due to his development and production of cheap and wholesome bread. The most famous item was the ''Belfast Bap'', more commonly known as ''Barney's Baps''. His bread is recalled in the rhyme:\n:''Barney Hughes' bread''\n:''Sticks to your belly like lead.''\nHis main mill was located in Divis Street in the lower [[Falls Road]].<ref>{{cite web |title=1884 Hungarian Flour Mill |url=http://archiseek.com/2017/1884-hungarian-flour-mills-divis-street-belfast/ |website=Archiseek |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe was the first Catholic elected to [[Belfast Corporation]]. He campaigned against sectarianism and for social justice.  He gave evidence to the Royal Commission of Inquiry into the sectarian riots of 1857 and 1864 which angered the Tory establishment in the city. Although he was sometimes in conflict with the Catholic church he gave land for the building of [[St. Peter's Cathedral, Belfast|St Peter's Cathedral]] in the Lower Falls area <ref>{{cite book |last1=Magee |first1=Jack |title=Barney: Bernard Hughes of Belfast |date=2001 |publisher=Ulster Historical Foundation |location=Belfast |isbn=1903688051 |pages=285}}</ref>\n\nHe is buried in ''Friar's Bush Graveyard'' - the oldest cemetery in Belfast.<ref>{{cite web |title=Friar's Bush |url=http://www.belfastcity.gov.uk/community/cemeteries/friarsbush.aspx |website=Belfast City Council |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hughes, Bernard}}\n[[Category:People from Belfast]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Belfast]]\n[[Category:Members of Belfast City Council]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:People from County Armagh]]\n[[Category:Irish philanthropists]]\n[[Category:1808 births]]\n[[Category:1878 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toFalls Road(link changed toFalls Road, Belfast) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernard_Hughes"}
{"title_page": "Arthur Brittenden", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n'''Charles Arthur Brittenden''' (23 October 1924 &ndash; 25 April 2015) was a British [[newspaper editor]]. A career journalist, he worked for ''[[Yorkshire Post]]'', ''[[Daily Express]]'' and ''[[Daily Mail]]'', before joining [[News International]], where he helped bring ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)]]'' up to the UK's top selling daily newspaper.\n\n==Biography==\nBrittenden was born in [[Leeds]] on 23 October 1924. His father Tom Edwin Brittenden was a cashier at a [[wool mill]] and his mother was Caroline Margaret Scrivener. His father would die when Brittenden was two, and the following year his mother married engineer William Esam. Brittenden attended Leeds grammar school until the age of 16, where he joined the ''[[Yorkshire Post]]'' where he remained for ten years, with a break for [[national service]].<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite web |last1=Kennedy |first1=Philippa |title=Brittenden, (Charles) Arthur (1924\u20132015) |url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-110412?rskey=RBfQwE&result=59 |website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=10 January 2019}}</ref><ref>Deborah Ross, \"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/barbara-taylor-bradford-a-woman-of-substance-420770.html Barbara Taylor Bradford: A woman of substance]\", ''[[The Independent]]'', 21 October 2006</ref>\n\nBrittenden married three times, first to Sylvia Penelope Cadman in 1953, then in 1966 to [[Ann Patricia Kenny]], the royal correspondent for ''[[Daily Telegraph]]''. His third marriage was on 24 October 1975, to Valerie Arnison, who he remained with until she died in 2002.<ref name=ODNB/> Brittenden himself died on 25 April 2015 at the age of 90.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/obituaries/article4423449.ece Arthur Brittenden]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nUpon leaving the ''Post'', Brittenden spent six years at ''[[News Chronicle]]'' before joining ''[[Sunday Express]]'', rising first to chief reporter then foreign editor in 1959. Three years later, in the early 1960s, he become Assistant Editor for the north of the ''[[Daily Express]]''. In 1966, he moved to become Editor of the ''[[Daily Mail]]''.<ref>David Haworth, \"Editor to tell Premier why he was sacked\", ''[[The Guardian]]'', 18 December 1966</ref>  He held the post until 1971, when the paper merged with the ''[[Daily Sketch]]'', and he was replaced by ''Sketch'' editor [[David English (editor)|David English]].<ref>[[Bill Hagerty]], \"[http://www.newstatesman.com/200012040043 Get a real editor, not a Dalek]\", ''[[New Statesman]]'', 4 December 2000</ref> Brittenden later moved to [[News International]], and from 1981 to 1987, he served as its Director of Corporate Relations.<ref>\"[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/court_and_social/article2714626.ece \"Birthdays\"], ''[[The Times]]'', 23 October 2007</ref> He worked with [[Larry Lamb]] and [[Bernard Shrimsley]] on bringing the ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' to the UK's highest circulating daily newspaper. [[Rupert Murdoch]], owner of ''The Sun'', would put Brittenden in charge of corporate relations for [[News International]] during the [[Wapping dispute]] in 1981, before moving him to editorial manager for [[Times Newspapers]] until his retirement in 1987.<ref name=ODNB/>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box|title=Deputy Editor of the ''[[Sunday Express]]''|years=1963&ndash;1964|before=?|after=?}}\n{{succession box|title=Editor of the ''[[Daily Mail]]''|years=1966&ndash;1971|before=[[Mike Randall (journalist)|Mike Randall]]|after=[[David English (editor)|David English]]}}\n{{succession box|title=Deputy Editor of ''[[The Sun (UK)|The Sun]]''|years=1972&ndash;1981|before=[[Peter Stephens (journalist)|Peter Stephens]]|after=?}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Daily Mail editors}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brittenden, Arthur}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:British newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:British newspaper executives]]\n[[Category:Daily Express people]]\n[[Category:Daily Mail journalists]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n'''Charles Arthur Brittenden''' (23 October 1924 &ndash; 25 April 2015) was a British [[newspaper editor]]. A career journalist, he worked for ''[[Yorkshire Post]]'', ''[[Daily Express]]'' and ''[[Daily Mail]]'', before joining [[News International]], where he helped bring ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)]]'' up to the UK's top selling daily newspaper. \n\n==Biography==\nBrittenden was born in [[Leeds]] on 23 October 1924. His father Tom Edwin Brittenden was a cashier at a [[wool mill]] and his mother was Caroline Margaret Scrivener. His father would die when Brittenden was two, and the following year his mother married engineer William Esam. Brittenden attended Leeds grammar school until the age of 16, where he joined the ''[[Yorkshire Post]]'' where he remained for ten years, with a break for [[national service]].<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite web |last1=Kennedy |first1=Philippa |title=Brittenden, (Charles) Arthur (1924\u20132015) |url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-110412?rskey=RBfQwE&result=59 |website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=10 January 2019}}</ref><ref>Deborah Ross, \"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/barbara-taylor-bradford-a-woman-of-substance-420770.html Barbara Taylor Bradford: A woman of substance]\", ''[[The Independent]]'', 21 October 2006</ref> \n\nBrittenden married three times, first to Sylvia Penelope Cadman in 1953, then in 1966 to [[Ann Patricia Kenny]], the royal correspondent for ''[[Daily Telegraph]]''. His third marriage was on 24 October 1975, to Valerie Arnison, who he remained with until she died in 2002.<ref name=ODNB/> Brittenden himself died on 25 April 2015 at the age of 90.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/obituaries/article4423449.ece Arthur Brittenden]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nUpon leaving the ''Post'', Brittenden spent six years at ''[[News Chronicle]]'' before joining ''[[Sunday Express]]'', rising first to chief reporter then foreign editor in 1959. Three years later, in the early 1960s, he become Assistant Editor for the north of the ''[[Daily Express]]''. In 1966, he moved to become Editor of the ''[[Daily Mail]]''.<ref>David Haworth, \"Editor to tell Premier why he was sacked\", ''[[The Guardian]]'', 18 December 1966</ref>  He held the post until 1971, when the paper merged with the ''[[Daily Sketch]]'', and he was replaced by ''Sketch'' editor [[David English (editor)|David English]].<ref>[[Bill Hagerty]], \"[http://www.newstatesman.com/200012040043 Get a real editor, not a Dalek]\", ''[[New Statesman]]'', 4 December 2000</ref> Brittenden later moved to [[News International]], and from 1981 to 1987, he served as its Director of Corporate Relations.<ref>\"[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/court_and_social/article2714626.ece \"Birthdays\"], ''[[The Times]]'', 23 October 2007</ref> He worked with [[Larry Lamb]] and [[Bernard Shrimsley]] on bringing the ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' to the UK's highest circulating daily newspaper. [[Rupert Murdoch]], owner of ''The Sun'', would put Brittenden in charge of corporate relations for [[News International]] during the [[Wapping dispute]] in 1981, before moving him to editorial manager for [[Times Newspapers]] until his retirement in 1987.<ref name=ODNB/>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box|title=Deputy Editor of the ''[[Sunday Express]]''|years=1963&ndash;1964|before=?|after=?}}\n{{succession box|title=Editor of the ''[[Daily Mail]]''|years=1966&ndash;1971|before=[[Mike Randall (journalist)|Mike Randall]]|after=[[David English (editor)|David English]]}}\n{{succession box|title=Deputy Editor of ''[[The Sun (UK)|The Sun]]''|years=1972&ndash;1981|before=[[Peter Stephens (journalist)|Peter Stephens]]|after=?}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Daily Mail editors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brittenden, Arthur}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:British newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:British newspaper executives]]\n[[Category:Daily Express people]]\n[[Category:Daily Mail journalists]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Brittenden"}
